          We in OBSCURE (tm), believe in the facts that the most important
          thing with a DVDR release is that the video and audio quality
          have the highest prioirty. Our goal is to release DVDR&#039;s with
          a video and audio quality that do not differ from the original
          disc. Due to these facts, we happily remove extras from
          a release to make room for the video and audio. For us, DVD
          (and DVDR) is about having the best availiable video and audio
          quality that this excellent format can handle, so that we get
          a thrilling experience on our HI-FI systems. Some DVD&#039;s though,
          are constructed in such a way that it is impossible not
          having to downsample the main movie even when all extras are
          gone, for instance when the movie is ~3 hours long and there is
          a DTS track on it. When these situations occur we use CCE
          with a minimum of 7 passes to encode the main movie to achieve
          a quality that is highly acceptable.
          
          Due to the fact that groups STILL use the term "COMPLETE" for
          releases that are not from a DVD5 source (releases that do
          not require any ripping, downsampling or any other altering)
          we have decided to stop using that term for our DVD5 releases.
          From now on we will tag our DVD5 releases with the term "DVD5"
          instead of "COMPLETE" to make sure there aren&#039;t any
          misunderstandings regarding the release being altered or
          untouched.
          DVD5 release = 1:1 copy from the original disc.

          We urge other groups out there to follow our examples, tagging
          releases DVD5 if the source is a DVD5 disc and for DVD9
          releases, keep the video and audio quality at its best.
          If this means removing extras, then do that!
          
          / OBSCURE
